# ORIG TITLE    Dresden anti-fascist protesters block neo-Nazi march . 
# ORIG CONTENT  More than 13,000 protesters in Dresden, Germany formed a human chain to block a neo-Nazi rally on February 13. One man explained why he came out in sub-zero temperatures to take part: “I think it’s important to support my city and show that there’s no place for extremists.” . Another anti-Nazi protester said: “I’m here in memory of war victims and to take a stand against racism.” . More than 3,000 police from across Germany were called to Dresden to ensure the parallel protests did not escalate into violent clashes. Authorities said the night was mostly peaceful – although two officers were injured by masked demonstrators and several people were arrested. 
